<TITLE> Thakurgaon court set for BDR trial verdict </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Thakurgaon, Apr 12 (bdnews24.com)  A special court in Thakurgaon is due give its verdict on Monday at 3pm in the trial of 51 members of the 20th Rifles Battalion accused of rebellion in support of the mutiny at the BDR's Pilkhana headquarters last year. BDR chief Maj Gen Mainul Islam, head of the three-member judge's panel, will hand down the verdict. The Thakurgaon court launched its trial on Feb 3 this year. It was adjourned on Feb 5 and resumed proceedings on Apr 8. A total of 33 people have testified in the case. Charges were pressed against 51 suspects last week, of them 44 have admitted their involvement in mutinous acts at Tahkurgaon on Feb 25=26 last year sparked by the mutiny and massacre at Pilkhana in Dhaka. The Pilkhana mutineers killed over 70 people, nearly 60 of them army officers deputed to the border force. Rebellion spread to other BDR outposts around the country. On November 15, the government formed six special courts, including two in Dhaka, to try about 3,500 border guards accused in 40 cases around the country. The six special courts are trying charges of mutiny, looting and arson. The Pilkhana killings will be tried separately in civilian courts. In the event of a guilty verdict by the special courts, the maximum penalty for rebellion under the BDR Act is seven years in jail. The special BDR court at Panchagarh on Apr 7 became the first to issue a verdict among the six courts across the country trying the BDR mutineers. It found all of the defendents guilty, handing down sentences ranging from four to seven years. Special BDR courts in Rangamati, Satkhira and Feni have also set verdict dates for ongoing trials. Verdicts in the trial of accused of 19th Rifles Battalion in Feni will be given on Apr 18; of 7th Rifles Battalion of Satkhira on Apr 19; and of Rajnagar Battalion of Rangamati on May 2. bdn
